prompt:
Our self-serve kiosks decide things like "does this cart get the member price" from little rule expressions that ops writes. The trees are already built for us (a parser feeds them in from the rules file); what we need is the evaluator, and I want it done properly with std::variant/std::visit instead of the enum-plus-union relic we have. C++20, stdlib only. Two new files: eval.hpp and eval.cpp.

The header must define exactly:

    using Value = std::variant<bool, long, std::string>;

    struct EvalError {
        std::string code;    // "undef" | "type" | "div0"
        std::string detail;  // undef: the variable name; type: the operator
                             // spelling; div0: ""
    };

    using Outcome = std::variant<Value, EvalError>;

    struct Expr;
    using ExprPtr = std::shared_ptr<Expr>;

    struct Lit    { Value v; };
    struct Ref    { std::string name; };
    struct Unary  { char op; ExprPtr operand; };           // '-' or '!'
    struct Binary { std::string op; ExprPtr lhs, rhs; };   // "+","-","*","/","==","!=","<","and","or"

    struct Expr { std::variant<Lit, Ref, Unary, Binary> node; };

    using Env = std::map<std::string, Value>;

    ExprPtr lit(Value v);
    ExprPtr ref(std::string name);
    ExprPtr un(char op, ExprPtr operand);
    ExprPtr bin(std::string op, ExprPtr lhs, ExprPtr rhs);

    Outcome eval(const ExprPtr& e, const Env& env);

Semantics — strict typing, no coercions anywhere, errors are VALUES (the kiosk must never throw or crash on a bad rule):

- Lit yields its value; Ref looks the name up in env, missing name -> EvalError{"undef", name}.
- Unary '-' negates a long; '!' negates a bool; wrong operand type (or an op char outside the two) -> {"type", "<op>"}.
- "-" and "*" need two longs. "+" adds two longs OR concatenates two strings; every other combination (including bools) -> {"type", "+"}.
- "/" needs two longs, truncates toward zero exactly like C++ (-7/2 is -3), and a zero right side -> {"div0", ""} — checked before dividing, obviously.
- "=="/"!=" compare two values of the SAME alternative (bool/bool, long/long, string/string) and yield a bool; mixed alternatives -> {"type", op}. "<" orders two longs or two strings (lexicographic); bools and mixed -> {"type", "<"}.
- "and"/"or" require a bool on the left, else {"type", op}. They SHORT-CIRCUIT: "and" with a false left yields false and never evaluates the right side; "or" with a true left yields true likewise — a skipped side's errors must not surface. An evaluated right side must be a bool, else {"type", op}.
- Any operator string not listed above -> {"type", op}.
- Evaluation is left-to-right and the first error encountered is the whole result: operand errors surface before the operator's own type check, left before right.
- eval is pure: no globals, no caching keyed on the tree — the same ExprPtr gets evaluated under many different envs and must answer from the env at hand. Callers guarantee non-null ExprPtrs.

Style note from review: this is textbook std::visit-with-overloaded-lambdas territory; make the dispatch exhaustive so adding a node type later is a compile error, not a runtime surprise. Only behavior is tested though.

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_eval.cpp are fixed.
